## Landing Page

## Overview
Create a public-facing Landing Page for LifeOps that communicates value proposition, highlights core features, provides a pricing snapshot, showcases testimonials, and includes strong CTAs for Sign Up and Book Demo. The page must be visually cohesive with the LifeOps design system and prepared for marketing analytics, A/B testing, and responsive behavior across devices.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A public marketing page for LifeOps’ multi-agent AI operating system, designed to convert visitors into users or trial signups.

Goals:
- Clearly articulate the LifeOps value proposition and the modular architecture (Projects, Content, Finance, Health, Cronjobs & Orchestration).
- Present feature highlights as scannable cards with visual emphasis on dense information yet readable at a glance.
- Provide a pricing snapshot with quick comparisons and a CTA to compare plans and select a suitable tier.
- Social proof through testimonials to build trust.
- Drive user action via prominent CTAs: Sign up / Book demo, with secondary actions (Learn more, Compare plans).
- Integrate cleanly with documentation and developer docs references (link to Documentation / Developer Docs).

Features connected:
- No dynamic host-dependent features on this page; it is a pure, public-facing marketing surface. All content should be easily updatable via CMS or static content injection.
- Prepare the page to surface dynamic pricing data, testimonials, and feature highlights pulled from a CMS or static JSON, with graceful fallbacks.

UI elements and how they should look:
- Hero Section: Large, bold headline and subheadline. Primary CTA: Create account / Sign up. Secondary CTA: Book demo. Hero illustration that visually conveys multi-agent orchestration.
- Features Overview: 4–5 feature cards with icons, short descriptor, and a CTA to learn more or see more details.
  - Features: Projects, Content, Finance, Health, Cronjobs & Orchestration.
- How It Works: A 3-step section describing agents, cronjobs, and approvals with simple visuals or icons.
- Pricing Teaser: Tier cards (e.g., Starter, Pro, Enterprise) with key differentiators; a “Compare plans” link.
- Integrations Strip: Logos of major partners/integrations (GitHub, Stripe, Plaid, Google, Health APIs).
- Testimonials: Short quotes with author names and roles.
- Footer: Links to About, Help, Docs, Privacy, Terms, Contact; social icons if applicable.
- Responsiveness: Desktop layout with prominent hero and side-by-side feature cards; tablet/mobile should stack sections with readable typography, preserved visual hierarchy.
- Accessibility: ARIA roles and semantic HTML; keyboard navigable CTAs; color contrast compliance.

API integrations:
- None required for this page; content should be fetchable from CMS or static JSON with safe fallbacks.

Connected Pages:
- Documentation / Developer Docs: Public docs for APIs, connectors, agent templates, and workflow schema reference. Include visible navigation anchor to the docs section (e.g., a footer link or a "Docs" CTA).

---

## Components to Build
- LandingHero
  - Props: title, subtitle, ctas, illustrationSrc
  - Behavior: responsive hero layout, CTA click handlers (navigate to signup, open demo modal)
- FeatureCard
  - Props: icon, title, description, ctaLabel, ctaHref
  - Behavior: hover elevation, accessible button
- FeaturesGrid
  - Props: list of FeatureCard data
  - Behavior: responsive grid, search-friendly descriptors
- HowItWorks
  - Props: steps [{ title, description, icon }]
  - Behavior: responsive 3-step visualization
- PricingTeaser
  - Props: tiers [{ id, name, features, price, ctaLabel }]
  - Behavior: responsive tier cards with a “Compare plans” link
- IntegrationsStrip
  - Props: logos array
  - Behavior: horizontally scrollable on small screens, accessible alt text
- Testimonials
  - Props: tests [{ quote, author, title }]
  - Behavior: slider or vertical stack with optional autoplay
- FooterLinks
  - Props: sections and links
  - Behavior: responsive layout, accessibility labels
- CMSBridge (optional)
  - Purpose: fetch content (title, subtitle, features, pricing, testimonials) from CMS or fallback to static data with null-safety
- GlobalLayout
  - Navbar: minimal public header with logo and docs link
  - Container / grid system aligned to design tokens

All components must guard against null/undefined values:
- Use data ?? [] patterns for arrays
- Validate shapes with Array.isArray checks
- Initialize state with useState<Type[]>([]) for arrays
- Validate API/doc data shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Use optional chaining for nested properties: obj?.prop?.subprop
- Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack: React + TypeScript (recommended), CSS-in-JS or CSS modules consistent with project standards
- Routing: Landing page route (e.g., /) with hash anchors to sections or smooth scroll
- State management: Local component state for UI (modals, menu toggles); no global mutation required
- Styling System: Implement according to Visual Style section; reuse existing design tokens (colors, typography, spacing)
- Accessibility: All interactive elements are keyboard accessible; alt text for images; aria-live regions for dynamic content
- Performance: Images and illustrations optimized; consider lazy loading for heavy assets
- Analytics hooks: Optional data attributes for CTA tracking (data-tracking-id)

Code safety patterns to apply:
- Always treat API or CMS data as potentially null: const pageData = data ?? {}; const features = Array.isArray(pageData.features) ? pageData.features : [];
- Guard all array operations: (features ?? []).map(...), (tiers ?? []).forEach(...)
- Correct useState defaults: const [pricing, setPricing] = useState<PriceTier[]>([]);
- Validate response shapes: const testimonials = Array.isArray(resp?.testimonials) ? resp.testimonials : [];
- Optional chaining: logo?.src, hero?.cta?.label

### Backend (if applicable)
- Not required for this page; provide endpoints only if you plan dynamic content:
  - GET /landing/content to fetch hero, features, pricing, testimonials, logos
  - Ensure responses are validated on the client as per API validation rules

### Integration
- CMS or static data layer integration:
  - Fetch landing page content from CMS endpoint or local static JSON
  - Fallback to hard-coded defaults to avoid render failures
  - Normalize data into expected shapes for components
- Documentation link integration:
  - Link to Documentation / Developer Docs with clear call-to-action button
- SEO & Meta:
  - Proper meta tags (title, description, OG tags)
  - Accessible landmarks and semantic HTML structure

---

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on the hero section with compelling value proposition and two CTAs: Sign up and Book demo.
2. User scrolls to Features Overview; each feature card highlights a core capability and may link to deeper docs or a modal.
3. User views How It Works to understand the three-step process (agents, cronjobs, approvals) with concise visuals.
4. User checks Pricing Teaser; can click Compare plans to view plan matrix.
5. User sees Integrations Strip showcasing widely-used tools; trust signals via testimonials appear further down.
6. User interacts with testimonials, then ends with Footer links for more information or support.
7. Actions (Sign up / Book demo) trigger navigation or modal flows integrated with the app’s auth/demo booking system.

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models
- FeatureCard: { id: string, icon: string, title: string, description: string, cta?: { label: string, href: string } }
- PricingTier: { id: string, name: string, price: string, features: string[], ctaLabel?: string }
- Testimonial: { id: string, quote: string, author: string, role?: string }
- SectionContent: { hero: { title: string, subtitle: string, ctas: [{ label: string, href: string }] }, features: FeatureCard[], howItWorks: [{ title, description, icon }], pricing: PricingTier[], testimonials: Testimonial[], integrations: string[] }

API Endpoints
- GET /landing-content (optional, CMS-backed)
- Response shape: { data: SectionContent | null }
- If not available, use static defaults with safe fallbacks

Security
- No sensitive data on the landing page; ensure no secrets are embedded in the frontend code
- If CMS is used, ensure proper read access tokens are stored securely (env vars) and not exposed in the client

Validation
- All responses must be validated at the consumer layer:
  - const content = Array.isArray(data?.features) ? data.features : []
  - const heroCtas = Array.isArray(data?.hero?.ctas) ? data.hero.ctas : []
  - etc.

Error handling
- If data fetch fails, render with gracefully degraded defaults and a non-intrusive alert or badge indicating content may be outdated

---

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Landing Hero renders with title, subtitle, and two CTAs; CTAs navigate to signup and book demo routes respectively.
- [ ] Features grid renders 4–5 feature cards with icons, titles, and descriptions; missing data falls back gracefully.
- [ ] How It Works section renders with 3 steps and accessible icons.
- [ ] Pricing Teaser renders 3 tiers with clear differentiators and a Compare plans link; data falls back to defaults if missing.
- [ ] Integrations strip shows all logos; layout remains responsive without overflow.
- [ ] Testimonials section renders 2–3 testimonials; missing testimonials does not crash rendering.
- [ ] Footer includes About, Help, Docs, Privacy, Terms, Contact links.
- [ ] All array operations guarded: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray checks, and useState([]) usage.
- [ ] API response shapes validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data?.features) ? response.data.features : [].
- [ ] Visual styling aligns with the given color palette, typography, spacing, and design elements.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Maintain the dark UI aesthetic, high-contrast typography, and careful use of accent colors
- Use 8px baseline grid with multiples; ensure 220–260px sidebar/content rhythm for any potential admin/editor components (though public page should optimally be full-width on large viewports)
- Implement card-based layout with rounded corners and subtle borders; hover interactions should be mindful and subtle
- Ensure readability and scannability for marketing content, with clear visual hierarchy and digestible copy blocks
- Favor accessibility, performance, and maintainability in code organization and theming

---

## Visual Style

Color Palette (as defined in PROJECT CONTEXT)
- Primary background: #0B0B0C
- Secondary surface: #151718
- Tertiary surface / panel outline: #1F1F20
- Primary text: #FFFFFF
- Secondary text: #9DA3A6
- Subtle text: #56595B
- Accent: #FF3B30
- Neutral highlight: #CFCFCF
- Soft highlight: #E6E7E8
- Supporting accents: teal #00C2A8, amber #FFB020, purple #8B5CF6
- Borders: rgba(255,255,255,0.03)
- Gradients: #111213 → #1A1A1B

Typography & Layout
- Font: Inter (or SF Pro Display / Roboto fallback)
- Hierarchy
  - Headings: 600–700, 20–28px
  - Card titles: 500–600, 14–16px
  - Body: 400, 12–14px
  - Microcopy: 300–400, 11–12px
- Spacing: 8px baseline grid
- Layout: Responsive grid; hero + features + 3-step + pricing + testimonials + integrations + footer
- Alignment: Left-aligned lists; card grids center/left as appropriate

Key Design Elements
- Card: dark elevated cards with 8–12px radius; gradient background, subtle borders, hover lift
- Navigation: left sidebar (if used in editor) with accent pills; top breadcrumb bar on internal docs
- Data Visualization: minimal charts or no charts on Landing Page; if present, use low-contrast axes and colored series
- Interactive Elements: primary actions with strong visual emphasis; secondary actions subdued

Design Philosophy
- Modern, dense, and developer-friendly marketing UI
- Clarity, control, and trust through consistent visuals and subtle depth
- Reusability and component-driven architecture to support future pages (docs, dashboards)

---

## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: Apply these rules in ALL generated code
1. Supabase-like results or mocked data: use nullish coalescing data ?? [] where appropriate
2. Array methods safety: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
3. React useState defaults for arrays: useState<Type[]>([])
4. API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
5. Optional chaining: use obj?.prop?.nested
6. Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

---

This prompt provides a complete blueprint for building the Landing Page and the Documentation page in LifeOps, with detailed component specifications, data safety rules, visual guidelines, and acceptance criteria. It emphasizes null-safety, type-safe data handling, and alignment with the requested design system. If you’d like, I can tailor content placeholders (hero text, feature copy, pricing tiers, testimonials) to your brand voice or export-ready JSON structures for CMS ingestion. for style.

CRITICAL DESIGN REQUIREMENTS:
- You MUST follow ALL design principles and patterns specified in the Design Reference above
- Do NOT deviate from the design specifications without explicit user permission
- Implement ALL visual design elements (colors, typography, spacing, shadows, animations) as specified
- Follow the layout patterns and component designs exactly as documented
- Ensure all interactions and micro-animations match the reference specifications

CRITICAL TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- React 18.3.1, React Router 6.30.1
- Tailwind CSS v3 with tailwind.config.js and custom keyframes
- @tailwindcss/typography plugin for rich text content
- Tailwind CSS animations (NOT Motion library or framer-motion)
- Sonner for toasts
- Recharts for data visualization
- Native fetch() with API utilities in src/lib/api.ts
- Design system with CSS custom properties
- Use RGB color values for theming
- When Supabase is configured: use Edge Functions for LLM and server-only logic; never expose API keys in the client

